 to seo all strango ani\nmals that Inhabit the earth, the au\nthorities of New York Central park\nbare bought a cow.\nMedicine Hat wants Its nam\nchanged. If Kalamazoo and Oshkosh\ncan be happy and prosperous, there\neema to be no reason why Medicine\nHat should not bo comfortable.\nDasket ball may be a perfectly love\nly game, but when It becomes neces\nsary to call upon ibe police to pry\nplayers apart It would seem that a re\nvised rule ot come sort might well be\nInserted.\nThere Is In California a fountain of\noil that gushes up to a height ot\n1EC feet Advocates of the conserva\ntion ot our natural resources might do\nveil to Insist that a lid should bo put\non this fountain.\nAn Austrian girl, who has Just been\nnaturalized In New York, says she bo-\ncamo a citizen of this nation because\nsbo loves tbo United States and the\nAmerican peoplo. That la tho kind of\ntltlzeu wo want.\nMoloant and Hoxsey laughed at dan\ncer \"as long as tho machine was all\nright.\" When man becomes perfect,\nnosslbly ho will Invent a macblno that\nIs perfect. Until then It Is safer to\nlearo flying to tho birds.\nAf man in a Philadelphia restaurant\ndlfccovercd 15 pearls In ono oyster\ntow. It hi evident that tbo restaurant-pearl\nfisheries exicct to yield a\ngood harvest OiIb season. It this Is to\nlio taken for n samplo beginning.\nOno out of every four graduates of\nHarvard earns nil or a part of the\nmoney needed to pay his expenses.\nWo can't seo why Harvard shouldn't\ncet as much glory out of this fact as\nhe does out of her athletic exploits.\nTho department of agriculture has\nbeen keeping tabe on tho number ot\ndeer shot in this country during tbe\n13 ear and has coouted up to L7.E00.\njitlll thero aro peoplo who love deer\nthat hao not been converted Into\nYcnicon.\nA New York doctor sajs that If\nwomen contliluo to wear tho quanti\nties of false puffs, rolls and switches\nnow In fashion tho next generation\nmay liavo llttlo or no hair to start\nwith. With raro exceptions tho pres\nent generation had nilehty llttlo hair\nto start with.\nTho chief forester says that 84 per\nrent, of tho forest fires In 1903 wcro\nduo to tho carelessness of railroads\nund persons using tho forests. This\nts about as bad as tho percentage ot\nbouso fires caused by carelessness.\nThe government has again changed\ntho name of tbo llfo-savlng station at\nthe west end of Nantucket Island\nwhich used to bo \"Great Neck,\" from\n\"Mnddequct\" to \"Maddaket.\" but wo\nahnll not learn to spell tho now name\nuntil wo bavo soino assuranco that II\nIsn't going to bu chanted again.\n0 s\nTRUSTS\nSENATOR TELLS PAN-AMERICAN\nCONFERENCE HE DEPLORE8\nOPERATIONS OF LAW.\nINDUSTRIAL EFFICIENCY HIT\nDeclares Government Is Duty Break\ning Up Organization Points to\nGerman Policy Henry White Tells\nof Value of Reciprocity.\nWashington. Senator Kllhu Hoot of\nNow York, In an address Friday at\nthe closing session of the I'an-Amcrl\ncan commercial conference, praised\nthe prlnclplo ot organization In bust\nncss and made n plea for the organl\nzatlon and combination of American\nbusiness men for tho promotion ot\ntrade with Latin America.\nHo deplored tho fact that tho opera\nIons of tho law against tho great In\ndustrlal organizations \"reduced tho\nIndustrial efficiency of the country.\n\"It Is Important to break up or\nganizations,\" said Mr. Hoot, \"when\nthey are monopolizing tho means of\nsubsistence, but there Is one way to\ncounteract this influence, and that Is\nby substituting organizations on\nsound basis, not violating any law\nbut securing tbo concerted action of\ngreat numbers of Americans who have\na common purpose.\n\"The great principle of organization\nwhich Is revolutionizing the business\nof tho world applies to tho extension\nof trade. Germany to a considerable\nextent requires a combination of her\nmanufacturers, producers and com\nmcrclal concerns: Japan also prac\ntically does this. Hut In tho United\nStates it cannot bo dono under gov\ncrnmcnt leadership because the peo\npie do not concelvo It to bo tho gov\nernmcnt's function. It seems to be\nrather that tho government Is taken\nup largely with breaking up organlza\ntlons and that reduces tho Industrial\nefficiency of tho country.\nSenator Root aroused enthusiasm\nby his closing remarks that nowhere\non earth were thero \"a more noble\nand admirable people among men\nthan In Latin-America.\" Ho ndded\nthat only when tho people of the\nUnited States realized this and en\ntercd Into real friendship with these\ncountries would they reach a basis\nwhere American trade could bo ad\nvanced.\nHenry White, formerly United\n8tates ambassador to France, spoke\nof tho value of reciprocity with all\nnations.\nPUT QUIETUS ON ANNEXATION\nHouse Finance Committee Report Ad\nversely on Bennet Resolution\nTaft Influence Succeeds.\nWashington. To offset tho Cana\ndlan annexation talk which the admin\nlstratlon feared might effect tho reel\nprocity ngrcement, tho house commit'\nteo on foreign nffairs by a vote of 9\nto 1, reported adversely Friday on tho\nresolutions Introduced by Represent\natlvo Ilcnnot of Now York for the\nopening of negotiations with Great\nBritain looking to the annexation of\nCanada.\nMr. Rennet was tho only member of\ntho committee who voted for tho res\nolution and tho action followed con\nfercnecs of Chairman Foster anil Act\nlng Chairman McCnll of tho ways\nand means body with President Taft\nOne of the Rennet resolutions asked\ntho president to report to tho bouse\nfor Its Information all tho facts con\ncerning any negotiations pending with\ntho Canadian or British government\nand whether any negotiations are\npending looking to Canadian nnncxa\ntlon. The other resolution, a con'\ncurrent one, requested tho president\n\"to enter upon and to prosecute from\ntlmo to tlmo such negotiations with\ntho British government as ho may\ndeem expedient for tho annexation\nof tbo Dominion of Canada to the\nUnited States.\"\nSEES A PROSPEROUS YEAR\nCharles M. Schwab Returns From Eu\nrope In Optlmlttlc Mood Over\nBusiness Outlook.\nNow York. Charles M. Schwnb re\nturned on tho Maurctanla Friday from\nhis midwinter vacation In Hurnpo a\nmore pronounced optimist as to tho\nworld-wide business outlook for the\nvenr than ho was when ho left New\nYork threo months ago.\n\"Kvery sign points to an unusually\nproserous year, not only In the\nUnited States, but throughout tho\nworld.\" said Mr. Schwnb. \"Tho de\npression that to n greater or less OX'\ntent extended around tbo world fob\nln-A'lni! our big nnnlc of 1907. nniie.irs\nto Imvo been replaced by n vigor of\nrnnllilpnei) and activity that nui-urs\nwell, IUisIiicsh In all linos is boom\nlng. nnd lu nothing more than In steel\nnnd Iron. Wo could htivo no bettor\nsign than this.\"\nBUI Shuts Out Circus Sideshow.\nDos Moines, In.- Tho Iowa netiato\nFriday pasted the Stoddard bill. 11 1\nrendv unused bv the house, tirnlilhtt-\nIng tbe exhibition In Iowa of mon\nstrosities and abnormal perrons, The\nbill will practically prohibit most\nrlrrtu sideshows In Iowa.\nBlanche Walth Stricken.\nPeoria. Ill Stnndlng In tho wings\nalt Inn her ruo Just beforo tl.o rise\nif the curtain Thursday, Blanche\nW'a'rh, the well-known r .tress, fell to\nho rti n a faint.\nANDREW CARNEGIE'S PEACE DOVE\nHe Can Either\nWAR IS THREATENED\nRUSSIA TELLS POWERS IT WILL\nMAKE MILITARY DEMONSTRA\nTION AGAINST CHINA.\nCHARGES TREATY VIOLATION\nCzar Orders Troops Rushed to III Dis\ntrict Across Border to Enforce\nFree Trade Demand Washington\nto Ask for Peace.\nSt. Petersburg. Becauso of China's\npersisting violation of tbo St. Peters\nburg trade treaty ot 1881, Russia\nThursday notified tbo governments ot\nGermany, Franco nnd Great Britain\nthat sho intended to mako a military\ndemonstration on the Husso-Chlnce\nfrontier. War seems certain between\ntbo two powers unless Chlnn backs\ndown from bcr present attitude.\nRussian troops will bo sent forth\nwith to tho district of III. Tho ex\ntent of tbe demonstration. It Is added\nIn the diplomatic note, will depend\nentirely upon the attltudo assumed\nby China.\nVital questions Involved are freo\ntrado in Mongolia, tbe extraterritorial\nrights of Russia In China anil the es\ntablishment of a Russian consulate at\nKeobdo, Mongolia.\nThero bavo been rumors recently of\nan Intention of Russia to bring pres\nsure to bear upon China because of al\nleged violations of tho Russo-Chlneso\ntreaty. That tho situation was acute,\nhowever, has been denied, both by tbo\nChinese foreign board and the Russian\nlegation at Peking. It has been admit\nted that there wcro differences In tho\nInterpretations of tho .international\nagreement as mado at St. Petersburg\nand at Peking. Tho treaty adopted\nIn 1881 expires this month nnd It has\nbeen reported that China was not will\ning to renew It at least not until cer\ntain modifications had been made.\nTho treaty of 1881 provided for tho\nrc-cstabllshment ot tho Chlneso gov\nernment In tho province of III, which\nhad been occupied by tho Russian arm\nies slnco 1871. Interest In the Russ\nChinese situation will have to da\nchiefly with tho attitude ot tho other\npowers, though RursI.th understand\ning with Japan and tho other powers\nwould nppear to have paved tho way\nfor any coercive measures contem\nplated agnlnst China,\nWashington. Tho Russian govern\nment has ordered several regiments\nof troops to tho Ilus.'o ChliH.Eo fron\ntier, according to intelligence rent to\ntho stato department hero by tho Rus\nsian government.\nTho United States stato department\nwill Immediately nsk both countries\nto submit their grievances to Tho\nHaguo tribunal nnd hold In abeyance\nnny hostile demonstrations' until that\nbody can act. This step will bo taken\nwith a knowlcdgo that Czar Nicholas\nhas always been a stanch supporter\nof Tho llugue court.\nDorothy Arnold Not Found.\nNew York. Miss Dorothy Arnold\nhiiH not been found, and her\nfriends have no more definite Informa\ntion today than they hutl CO days ugo\nan to whnt haB become of her. Inquiry\ndemonstrated that a story to tho effect\nthat sho had been found In Flower\nhospital wus untrue.\nKansas Farmers Oppose Reciprocity.\nSalino, Kan. Four hundred farm\ners, delegutes to tho annual conven\ntion of tbo Kansas organizations of\ntho Farmer' Kducntlonul and Cc-optr-atlve\nUnion of Amerlcn, hero Thurs\nday unanimously condemned tho Can\nadian reciprocity agreement as dcjrl-\nnk'utnl to tho farmers' Interests.\nFavor VoWs for Women.\nIlea Moines, la. Tho houso commit-\nto mi elections Thursday recommend\ned for papsago tho Joint resolution fa\nvoring woman tsuffrnjo\nCoo or Claw.\nUNDER MARTIAL LAW\nGEN. NAVARRO CLAMPS LID ON\nJUAREZ COMPLETELY.\nFederal Troops Take Charge of Bon\nder City New Battle Is Fought\nNear Mexican.\nEl Paso, Tex. Juarez Is under mar\ntial law. General Navarro has taken\npossession of tho Mexico-Northwestern\nrailway, closed every business\nhouse, saloon and gambling places\nand Is in full control of tho city.\nlour express wagons, loaded with\narms and ammunitions, were captured\nby United States troops whllo they\nwcro attempting to cross tho river\nnear Falscns, east of this city. Eight\nMexicans and two Americans nccom\npanylng tho wagons wcro arrested.\nA battlo between Mexican troops\nand tbo insurgents took placo when\nabout thirty Mexican soldiers ad\nvanced from tho desert and took up a\nposition immediately opposite Mcxl\ncall. The soldiers fired 30 shots be\nforo tho Insurgents replied. Tho In\nsurgenta were scattered nlong tho\nriver bank on tbe Mexlcall side, using\ntbo ravines for breastworks.\nThe United States troops aro massed\nat tho boundary line, whllo artillery\nmen aro thrown along tho lino In front\nof tbo custom bouse. Hundreds\nwatched tho battlo from house tops.\nIt Is learned positively that Francis\nco I. Madero, lnsurrccto provisional\npresident of Mexico, Is t Guadalupe\nwith Abram Gonzales and members of\ntho lnsurrccto board of strategy. This\nIs admitted by members of tho Mcxl\ncan lnsurrccto Junta In El Paso.\nWILL SUE LUMBER BARONS\nDepartment of Justice Is Preparing Its\nCase Report of Commissioner\nSent to Congress.\nWashington. Two sharp blows at\ntho ro-called lumber trust were struck\nby tho administration Tuesday.\nOno wns n statement from tho de\npartment of justice that suit Is to bo\nfiled agnlust tho combtno based on\ncomplaints of discrimination, black,\nlisting, price raising and apportion\nment of territory.\nTho other was a report by Herbert\nKnox Smith, commissioner of corpora\ntions, showing tlio enormous extent\nof tho holdings of tho timber Inter\ncstH, giving warning of monopoly at no\ndistant date, relating tbo steady In\ncrease in prices and predicting still\ngreater advnncca by those who nro\nengaged In cornering tho forest re\nsources of tho country for speculative\npurposes. This report was sent to\ncongress by President Taft.\nGOMPERS APPEALS FOR AID\nSeeks to Raise $500,000 to Be Used In\nLos Angeles Labor\nFight.\nWashington. Samuel Gompcrs,\npresident of tho American Feder\nation of Iibor, bas sent to all labor\norganizations throughout tho country\na circular' asking aid In raising n fund\nof half a million dollars to bo used In\nfighting opponents of organized labor\nat I)S Angeles.\n\"Wo nro Issuing this npprnl,\" sold\n.Mr. GomptTH, \"for tho purporq of aid\ning our fclloV worklngmcn In Los\nAngeles to maintain their rights and\nliberties as men of organized labor.\"\nSugar Concern In Court.\nHouston, Tex. A receiver wus Fri\nday apiiolnted for tho Ohio and Texns\nSugar company, which has assets\nestimated nt 1,800,000. Tho holders\nof claims for $200 say tho company\nIs .virtually Insolvent.\nJohn D.'s Brother Is III.\nNew York. WUIIum Rockefeller,\nbrother of John D. Rockefeller and\nactive for years In the management\not tho Standard OU company, wus\nconfined to his homo with lumbago\nFriday\nGONRDENGESHOWN\nIndustrial Awakening Spring Buying\nFirm Prices Hope for Futu\nCollections Bet